# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anti-aliasing-graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] All generations of DLSS are available on all RTX-branded cards from Nvidia in supported titles.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] However, the Frame Generation feature is only supported on RTX 40 series GPUs or newer and Multi Frame Generation is only available on 50 series GPUs.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia advertised DLSS as a key feature of GeForce RTX 20 series GPUs when they launched in September 2018.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] At that time, the results were limited to a few video games, namely *Battlefield V*, or *Metro Exodus*, because the algorithm had to be trained specifically on each game on which it was applied and the results were usually not as good as simple resolution upscaling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In 2019, *Control* shipped with ray tracing and an image processing algorithm that approximated DLSS, which did not use the Tensor Cores.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In April 2020, Nvidia advertised and shipped an improved version of DLSS named DLSS 2 with driver version 445.75.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2.0 was available for a few existing games including *Control* and *Wolfenstein: Youngblood*, and would later be added to many newly released games and game engines such as Unreal Engine and Unity.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This time Nvidia said that it used the Tensor Cores again, and that the AI did not need to be trained specifically on each game.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Despite sharing the DLSS branding, the two iterations of DLSS differ significantly and are not backwards-compatible.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In January 2025, Nvidia stated that there are over 540 games and apps supporting DLSS, and that over 80% of Nvidia RTX users activate DLSS.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In March 2025, there were more than 100 games that support DLSS 4, according to Nvidia.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] By May 2025, over 125 games supported DLSS 4.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first video game console to use DLSS, the Nintendo Switch 2, was released on June 5, 2025.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In January 2026, Nvidia stated that over 250 games and applications support Multi Frame Generation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] On March 16, 2026, at GTC 2026, Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang presented DLSS 5, a real-time AI model based on neural rendering that realistically enhances lighting and material surfaces at up to 4K resolution while retaining the developer's intended art style.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It is planned to release in fall of 2026.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In a blog post on its website, Nvidia has announced that DLSS 5 will be available in such games as *Assassin's Creed Shadows*, *Delta Force*, *Hogwarts Legacy*, *Naraka: Bladepoint*, *Phantom Blade Zero*, *Resident Evil Requiem*, *Starfield*, *The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion Remastered*, and more.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] On May 31, 2026, Nvidia announced an updated version of Ray Reconstruction for DLSS 4.5 in a blog post, scheduled for release on all RTX GPUs in August of the same year.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] They said it is designed to better embed spatial awareness into scenes and analyze engine data on movements and lighting conditions, resulting in a sharper, more stable, and less noisy image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first iteration of DLSS is a predominantly spatial image upscaler with two stages, both relying on convolutional auto-encoder neural networks.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first step is an image enhancement network which uses the current frame and motion vectors to perform edge enhancement, and spatial anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The second stage is an image upscaling step which uses the single raw, low-resolution frame to upscale the image to the desired output resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Using just a single frame for upscaling means the neural network itself must generate a large amount of new information to produce the high-resolution output, which can result in slight hallucinations such as leaves that differ in style to the source content.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The neural networks are trained on a per-game basis by generating a "perfect frame" using traditional supersampling to 64 samples per pixel, as well as the motion vectors for each frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The data collected must be as comprehensive as possible, including as many levels, times of day, graphical settings, resolutions, etc. as possible.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This data is also augmented using common augmentations such as rotations, colour changes, and random noise to help generalize the test data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Training is performed on Nvidia's Saturn V supercomputer.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia also demonstrated the ability for the auto-encoder networks to learn the ability to recreate depth-of-field and motion blur, although this functionality has never been included in a publicly released product.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2 is a temporal anti-aliasing upsampling (TAAU) implementation, using data from previous frames extensively through sub-pixel jittering to resolve fine detail and reduce aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The data DLSS 2 collects includes: the raw low-resolution input, motion vectors, depth buffers, and exposure / brightness information.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It can also be used as a simpler TAA implementation where the image is rendered at 100% resolution, rather than being upsampled by DLSS, Nvidia brands this as DLAA (Deep Learning Anti-Aliasing).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] TAA(U) is used in many modern video games and game engines; however, all previous implementations have used some form of manually written heuristics to prevent temporal artifacts such as ghosting and flickering.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] One example of this is neighborhood clamping which forcefully prevents samples collected in previous frames from deviating too much compared to nearby pixels in newer frames.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This helps to identify and fix many temporal artifacts, but deliberately removing fine details in this way is analogous to applying a blur filter, and thus the final image can appear blurry when using this method.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2 uses a convolutional auto-encoder neural network trained to identify and fix temporal artifacts, instead of manually programmed heuristics as mentioned above.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Because of this, DLSS 2 can generally resolve detail better than other TAA and TAAU implementations, while also removing most temporal artifacts.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This is why DLSS 2 can sometimes produce a sharper image than rendering at higher, or even native resolutions using traditional TAA.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] However, no temporal solution is perfect, and artifacts (ghosting in particular) are still visible in some scenarios when using DLSS 2.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Because temporal artifacts occur in most art styles and environments in broadly the same way, the neural network that powers DLSS 2 does not need to be retrained when being used in different games.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Despite this, Nvidia does frequently ship new minor revisions of DLSS 2 with new titles, so this could suggest some minor training optimizations may be performed as games are released, although Nvidia does not provide changelogs for these minor revisions to confirm this.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The main advancements compared to DLSS 1 include: Significantly improved detail retention, a generalized neural network that does not need to be re-trained per-game, and ~2x less overhead (~1–2 ms vs ~2–4 ms).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It should also be noted that forms of TAAU such as DLSS 2 are not upscalers in the same sense as techniques such as ESRGAN or DLSS 1, which attempt to create new information from a low-resolution source; instead, TAAU works to recover data from previous frames, rather than creating new data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] In practice, this means low resolution textures in games will still appear low-resolution when using current TAAU techniques.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This is why Nvidia recommends game developers use higher resolution textures than they would normally for a given rendering resolution by applying a mip-map bias when DLSS 2 is enabled.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Augments DLSS 2 with improved image quality and the introduction of a new motion interpolation feature, called Frame Generation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The DLSS Frame Generation algorithm takes two rendered frames from the rendering pipeline and generates a new frame that smoothly transitions between them.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] For every frame rendered, one additional frame is generated.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 3.0 makes use of a new generation Optical Flow Accelerator (OFA) included in the Ada Lovelace architecture of GeForce RTX 40 series GPUs and with that is exclusive to them.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The new OFA is said to be faster and more accurate than the one already available in previous Turing and Ampere RTX GPUs.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 3.5 adds Ray Reconstruction, replacing multiple denoising algorithms with a single AI model trained on five times more data than DLSS 3.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Ray Reconstruction is available on all RTX GPUs and first targeted games with path tracing (aka "full ray tracing"), including *Cyberpunk 2077'*s *Phantom Liberty* DLC, *Portal with RTX*, and *Alan Wake 2*.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The fourth generation of DLSS was unveiled alongside the GeForce RTX 50 series.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4 upscaling uses a new vision transformer-based model for enhanced image quality with reduced ghosting and greater image stability in motion compared to the previous convolutional neural network (CNN) model.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4 allows a greater number of frames to be generated and interpolated based on a single traditionally rendered frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] This form of frame generation called Multi Frame Generation is exclusive to the GeForce RTX 50 series while the GeForce RTX 40 series is limited to one interpolated frame per traditionally rendered frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia claims that DLSS 4x Frame Generation model uses 30% less video memory with the example of *Warhammer 40,000: Darktide* using 400MB less memory at 4K resolution with Frame Generation enabled.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia claims that 75 games will integrate DLSS 4 Multi Frame Generation at launch, including *Alan Wake 2*, *Cyberpunk 2077*, *Indiana Jones and the Great Circle*, and *Star Wars Outlaws*.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4.5 introduces Dynamic Multi Frame Generation, which can dynamically generate up to 6x the amount of frames for GeForce RTX 50-series GPUs, and upgrades the transformer model used for upscaling to a second-generation model for better temporal stability, ghosting and anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 5, announced at GTC 2026, uses a neural rendering-based AI model to enhance lighting and material surfaces in real time at up to 4K resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia described the technology as retaining the developer's intended art style, while using color and motion-vector data to generate temporally stable lighting and material effects.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS requires and applies its own anti-aliasing method.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Thus, depending on the game and quality setting used, using DLSS may improve image quality even over native resolution rendering.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It operates on similar principles to TAA.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Like TAA, it uses information from past frames to produce the current frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Unlike TAA, DLSS does not sample every pixel in every frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Instead, it samples different pixels in different frames and uses pixels sampled in past frames to fill in the unsampled pixels in the current frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS uses machine learning to combine samples in the current frame and past frames, and is made possible by the available tensor cores.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia also offers Deep Learning Anti-Aliasing (DLAA), which provides the same AI-driven anti-aliasing DLSS uses, but without any upscaling or downscaling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] With the exception of the shader-core version implemented in *Control*, DLSS is only available on GeForce RTX 20, GeForce RTX 30, GeForce RTX 40, GeForce RTX 50, and Quadro RTX series of video cards, using dedicated AI accelerators called **Tensor Cores**.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Tensor Cores are available since the Nvidia Volta GPU microarchitecture, which was first used on the Tesla V100 line of products.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] They are used for doing fused multiply-add (FMA) operations that are used extensively in neural network calculations for applying a large series of multiplications on weights, followed by the addition of a bias.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Tensor cores can operate on FP16, INT8, INT4, and INT1 data types.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Each core can do 1024 bits of FMA operations per clock, so 1024 INT1, 256 INT4, 128 INT8, and 64 FP16 operations per clock per tensor core, and most Turing GPUs have a few hundred tensor cores.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The Tensor Cores use CUDA Warp-Level Primitives on 32 parallel threads to take advantage of their parallel architecture.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] A Warp is a set of 32 threads which are configured to execute the same instruction.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Since Windows 10 version 1903, Microsoft provided DirectML as one part of DirectX to support Tensor Cores.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The linear scale factor used for upsampling the input resolution to the output resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, a scene rendered at 540p with a 2.00x scale factor would have an output resolution of 1080p.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The linear render scale, compared to the output resolution, that the technology uses to render scenes internally before upsampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, a 1080p scene with a 50% render scale would have an internal resolution of 540p.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Users can manually replace the DLLs in games to support a newer version of DLSS.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS Swapper, an open source utility, can automatically do this for all installed games.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Replacing DLL files can not add DLSS support or features to games that do not already implement them, though some mods can add frame generation support.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It is also possible to override the DLSS version without touching game files via the Nvidia App.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] While the Nvidia App does not specify the DLSS version used in each preset available, the following table summarizes this information.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Particularly in early versions of DLSS, users reported blurry frames.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Andrew Edelsten, an employee at Nvidia, therefore commented on the problem in a blog post in 2019 and promised that they were working on improving the technology and clarified that the DLSS AI algorithm was mainly trained with 4K image material.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] That the use of DLSS leads to particularly blurred images at lower resolutions, such as Full HD, is due to the fact that the algorithm has far less image information available to calculate an appropriate image compared to higher resolutions like 4K.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The use of DLSS Frame Generation leads to increased input latency, as well as visual artifacts.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] It has also been criticized that by implementing DLSS in their games, game developers no longer have an incentive to optimize them so that they also run smoothly in native resolution on modern PC hardware.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, for the game *Alan Wake 2* in 4K at the highest graphics settings with ray tracing enabled, the use of DLSS in Performance mode is recommended even with graphics cards such as the Nvidia GeForce RTX 4080 in order to achieve 60 fps.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Upon its announcement at GTC 2026, DLSS 5 received significant backlash from both gamers and game developers on social media.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] Critics argued that the technology's neural rendering-based approach altered games' art direction in ways not intended by their developers, with some comparing its output to AI slop.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] The technology's handling of human faces drew particular criticism.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] *The Verge* highlighted an example from *EA Sports FC 26* in which Liverpool captain Virgil van Dijk's facial features were noticeably distorted by the technology, and compared the overall effect to motion smoothing on televisions.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/deep-learning-super-sampling] *IGN* characterized DLSS 5 as undermining the artistic craft of video game design, and *Engadget* argued that the negative reaction from gamers was justified.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] FXAA 3 is released under a public domain license.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] A later version, FXAA 3.11, is released under a 3-clause BSD license.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] This data could be passed into the FXAA algorithm from the rendering step as an alpha channel embedded into the image to be antialiased, calculated from the rendered image, or approximated by using the green channel as the luminance data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Find high contrast pixels by using a high pass filter that uses the luminance data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Low contrast pixels that are found are excluded from being further altered by FXAA.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] The high pass filter that excludes low contrast pixels can be tuned to balance speed and sensitivity.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Use contrast between adjacent pixels to heuristically find edges, and determine whether the edges are in the horizontal or vertical directions.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] The blend direction of a pixel will be perpendicular to the detected edge direction on that pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Calculate one blend factor for a high-contrast pixel by analyzing the luminance data in the 3x3 grid of pixels with the pixel in question being the center pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Search along the detected edge to determine how long that edge goes for and what direction the actual edge goes when the detected horizontal or vertical edge ends in order to take into account the actual edge's direction in order to calculate a second blend factor.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] This step can be tuned for more quality by increasing the search resolution and how far the search goes before the search for the edge's end gives up, or for more speed by reducing both.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Blend the pixel using the chosen blend direction and the maximum of both of the blend factors that were calculated.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] The main advantage of this technique over conventional spatial anti-aliasing is that it does not require large amounts of computing power.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] It achieves this by smoothing undesirable jagged edges ("jaggies") as pixels, according to how they appear on-screen, rather than analyzing the 3D model itself, as in conventional spatial anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] Since it is not based on the actual geometry, it will smooth not only edges between triangles, but also edges inside alpha-blended textures, or those resulting from pixel shader effects, which are immune to the effects of multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] FXAA includes a specific sub-pixel low-pass filter pass to reduce shimmering and aliasing in shader results such as shadows and specular highlights.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/fast-approximate-anti-aliasing] This stage uses a low-pass filter on 3x3 neighborhoods to dampen high-frequency artifacts, helping to reduce "shimmering" or "stipple" aliasing in moving images.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] It is an optimization of supersampling, where only the necessary parts are sampled more.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Jaggies are only noticed in a small area, so the area is quickly found, and only that is anti-aliased.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The term generally refers to a special case of supersampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Initial implementations of full-scene anti-aliasing (FSAA) worked conceptually by simply rendering a scene at a higher resolution, and then downsampling to a lower-resolution output.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Most modern GPUs are capable of this form of anti-aliasing, but it greatly taxes resources such as texture, bandwidth, and fillrate.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] According to the OpenGL GL_ARB_multisample specification, "multisampling" refers to a specific optimization of supersampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The specification dictates that the renderer evaluate the fragment program once per pixel, and only "truly" supersample the depth and stencil values.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In graphics literature in general, "multisampling" refers to any special case of supersampling where some components of the final image are not fully supersampled.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The lists below refer specifically to the ARB_multisample definition.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In supersample anti-aliasing, multiple locations are sampled within every pixel, and each of those samples is fully rendered and combined with the others to produce the pixel that is ultimately displayed.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] This is computationally expensive, because the entire rendering process must be repeated for each sample location.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] It is also inefficient, as aliasing is typically only noticed in *some* parts of the image, such as the edges, whereas supersampling is performed for every single pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In multisample anti-aliasing, if any of the multi sample locations in a pixel is covered by the triangle being rendered, a shading computation must be performed for that triangle.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] However this calculation only needs to be performed *once* for the whole pixel regardless of how many sample positions are covered; the result of the shading calculation is simply applied to *all* of the relevant multi sample locations.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In the case where only one triangle covers every multi sample location within the pixel, only one shading computation is performed, and these pixels are little more expensive than (and the result is no different from) the non-anti-aliased image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] This is true of the middle of triangles, where aliasing is not an issue.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The shading calculation is not the only operation that must be performed on a given pixel; multisampling implementations may variously sample other operations such as visibility at different sampling levels.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Alpha testing is a technique common to older video games used to render translucent objects by rejecting pixels from being written to the framebuffer.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] If the alpha value of a translucent fragment (pixel) is below a specified threshold, it will be discarded.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Because this is performed on a pixel by pixel basis, the image does not receive the benefits of multi-sampling (all of the multisamples in a pixel are discarded based on the alpha test) for these pixels.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The resulting image may contain aliasing along the edges of transparent objects or edges within textures, although the image quality will be no worse than it would be without any anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Translucent objects that are modelled using alpha-test textures will also be aliased due to alpha testing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] This effect can be minimized by rendering objects with transparent textures multiple times, although this would result in a high performance reduction for scenes containing many transparent objects.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Because multi-sampling calculates interior polygon fragments only once per pixel, aliasing and other artifacts will still be visible inside rendered polygons where fragment shader output contains high frequency components.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] While less performance-intensive than SSAA (supersampling), it is possible in certain scenarios (scenes heavy in complex fragments) for MSAA to be multiple times more intensive for a given frame than post processing anti-aliasing techniques such as FXAA, SMAA and MLAA.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Early techniques in this category tend towards a lower performance impact, but suffer from accuracy problems.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In a point-sampled mask, the coverage bit for each multisample is only set if the multisample is located inside the rendered primitive.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Filtering quality can be improved by using area sampled masks.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] In this method, the number of bits set in a coverage mask for a pixel should be proportionate to the actual area coverage of the fragment.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] This will result in some coverage bits being set for multisamples that are not actually located within the rendered primitive, and can cause aliasing and other artifacts.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] A regular grid sample pattern, where multisample locations form an evenly spaced grid throughout the pixel, is easy to implement and simplifies attribute evaluation (i.e. setting subpixel masks, sampling color and depth).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] This method is computationally expensive due to the large number of samples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Edge optimization is poor for screen-aligned edges, but image quality is good when the number of multisamples is large.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] A sparse regular grid sample pattern is a subset of samples that are chosen from the regular grid sample pattern.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] As with the regular grid, attribute evaluation is simplified due to regular spacing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The method is less computationally expensive due to having a fewer samples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Edge optimization is good for screen aligned edges, and image quality is good for a moderate number of multisamples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] A stochastic sample pattern is a random distribution of multisamples throughout the pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The irregular spacing of samples makes attribute evaluation complicated.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The method is cost efficient due to low sample count (compared to regular grid patterns).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Edge optimization with this method, although sub-optimal for screen aligned edges.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Image quality is excellent for a moderate number of samples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Compared to supersampling, multisample anti-aliasing can provide similar quality at higher performance, or better quality for the same performance.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Further improved results can be achieved by using rotated grid subpixel masks.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] The additional bandwidth required by multi-sampling is reasonably low if Z and colour compression are available.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Most modern GPUs support 2×, 4×, and 8× MSAA samples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/multisample-anti-aliasing] Higher values result in better quality, but are slower.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital signal processing, **spatial anti-aliasing** is a technique for minimizing the distortion artifacts (aliasing) when representing a high-resolution image at a lower resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is used in digital photography, computer graphics, digital audio, and many other applications.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing means removing signal components that have a higher frequency than is able to be properly resolved by the recording (or sampling) device.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This removal is done before (re)sampling at a lower resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When sampling is performed without removing this part of the signal, it causes undesirable artifacts such as black-and-white noise.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In signal acquisition and audio, anti-aliasing is often done using an analog anti-aliasing filter to remove the out-of-band component of the input signal prior to sampling with an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital photography, optical anti-aliasing filters made of birefringent materials smooth the signal in the spatial optical domain.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The anti-aliasing filter essentially blurs the image slightly in order to reduce the resolution to or below that achievable by the digital sensor (the larger the pixel pitch, the lower the achievable resolution at the sensor level).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, anti-aliasing improves the appearance of "jagged" polygon edges, or "jaggies", so they are smoothed out on the screen.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, it incurs a performance cost for the graphics card and uses more video memory.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The level of anti-aliasing determines how smooth polygon edges are (and how much video memory it consumes).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Near the top of an image with a receding checker-board pattern, the image is difficult to recognise and often not considered aesthetically pleasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In contrast, when anti-aliased the checker-board near the top blends into grey, which is usually the desired effect when the resolution is insufficient to show the detail.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Even near the bottom of the image, the edges appear much smoother in the anti-aliased image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Multiple methods exist, including the sinc filter, which is considered a better anti-aliasing algorithm.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When magnified, it can be seen how anti-aliasing interpolates the brightness of the pixels at the boundaries to produce grey pixels since the space is occupied by both black and white tiles.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These help make the sinc filter antialiased image appear much smoother than the original.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In a simple diamond image, anti-aliasing blends the boundary pixels; this reduces the aesthetically jarring effect of the sharp, step-like boundaries that appear in the aliased graphic.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is often applied in rendering text on a computer screen, to suggest smooth contours that better emulate the appearance of text produced by conventional ink-and-paper printing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Particularly with fonts displayed on typical LCD screens, it is common to use subpixel rendering techniques like ClearType.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sub-pixel rendering requires special colour-balanced anti-aliasing filters to turn what would be severe colour distortion into barely-noticeable colour fringes.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Equivalent results can be had by making individual sub-pixels addressable as if they were full pixels, and supplying a hardware-based anti-aliasing filter as is done in the OLPC XO-1 laptop's display controller.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Pixel geometry affects all of this, whether the anti-aliasing and sub-pixel addressing are done in software or hardware.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most basic approach to anti-aliasing a pixel is determining what percentage of the pixel is occupied by a given region in the vector graphic - in this case a pixel-sized square, possibly transposed over several pixels - and using that percentage as the colour.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This method is generally best suited for simple graphics, such as basic lines or curves, and applications that would otherwise have to convert absolute coordinates to pixel-constrained coordinates, such as 3D graphics.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is a fairly fast function, but it is relatively low-quality, and gets slower as the complexity of the shape increases.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] For purposes requiring very high-quality graphics or very complex vector shapes, this will probably not be the best approach.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Note: The `plot_antialiased_point` routine above cannot blindly set the colour value to the percent calculated.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It must **add** the new value to the existing value at that location up to a maximum of 1.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Otherwise, the brightness of each pixel will be equal to the darkest value calculated in time for that location which produces a very bad result.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] For example, if one point sets a brightness level of 0.90 for a given pixel and another point calculated later barely touches that pixel and has a brightness of 0.05, the final value set for that pixel should be 0.95, not 0.05.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In this approach, the ideal image is regarded as a *signal*.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The image displayed on the screen is taken as samples, at each (*x,y*) pixel position, of a filtered version of the signal.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Ideally, one would understand how the human brain would process the original signal, and provide an on-screen image that will yield the most similar response by the brain.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most widely accepted analytic tool for such problems is the Fourier transform; this decomposes a signal into basis functions of different frequencies, known as frequency components, and gives us the amplitude of each frequency component in the signal.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] where *j* and *k* are arbitrary non-negative integers.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are also frequency components involving the sine functions in one or both dimensions, but for the purpose of this discussion, the cosine will suffice.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The numbers *j* and *k* together are the *frequency* of the component: *j* is the frequency in the *x* direction, and *k* is the frequency in the *y* direction.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Current knowledge of human visual perception is not sufficient, in general, to say what approach will look best.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The previous discussion assumes that the rectangular mesh sampling is the dominant part of the problem.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The filter usually considered optimal is not rotationally symmetrical, as shown in this first figure; this is because the data is sampled on a square lattice, not using a continuous image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This sampling pattern is the justification for doing signal processing along each axis, as it is traditionally done on one dimensional data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Lanczos resampling is based on convolution of the data with a discrete representation of the sinc function.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If the resolution is not limited by the rectangular sampling rate of either the source or target image, then one should ideally use rotationally symmetrical filter or interpolation functions, as though the data were a two dimensional function of continuous x and y.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The sinc function of the radius has too long a tail to make a good filter (it is not even square-integrable).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] A more appropriate analog to the one-dimensional sinc is the two-dimensional Airy disc amplitude, the 2D Fourier transform of a circular region in 2D frequency space, as opposed to a square region.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] One might consider a Gaussian plus enough of its second derivative to flatten the top (in the frequency domain) or sharpen it up (in the spatial domain), as shown.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Functions based on the Gaussian function are natural choices, because convolution with a Gaussian gives another Gaussian whether applied to x and y or to the radius.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Similarly to wavelets, another of its properties is that it is halfway between being localized in the configuration (x and y) and in the spectral (j and k) representation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an interpolation function, a Gaussian alone seems too spread out to preserve the maximum possible detail, and thus the second derivative is added.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an example, when printing a photographic negative with plentiful processing capability and on a printer with a hexagonal pattern, there is no reason to use sinc function interpolation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Such interpolation would treat diagonal lines differently from horizontal and vertical lines, which is like a weak form of aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are only a handful of primitives used at the lowest level in a real-time rendering engine (either software or hardware accelerated).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These include "points", "lines" and "triangles".
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one is to draw such a primitive in white against a black background, it is possible to design such a primitive to have fuzzy edges, achieving some sort of anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, this approach has difficulty dealing with adjacent primitives (such as triangles that share an edge).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] To approximate the uniform averaging algorithm, one may use an extra buffer for sub-pixel data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The initial (and least memory-hungry) approach used 16 extra bits per pixel, in a 4 × 4 grid.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one renders the primitives in a careful order, such as front-to-back, it is possible to create a reasonable image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Since this requires that the primitives be in some order, and hence interacts poorly with an application programming interface such as OpenGL, the latest methods simply have two or more full sub-pixels per pixel, including full color information for each sub-pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There is also an approach specialised for texture mapping called mipmapping, which works by creating lower resolution, pre-filtered versions of the texture map.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When rendering the image, the appropriate-resolution mipmap is chosen and hence the texture pixels (texels) are already filtered when they arrive on the screen.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Mipmapping is generally combined with various forms of texture filtering in order to improve the final result.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because fractals have unlimited detail and no noise other than arithmetic round-off error, they illustrate aliasing more clearly than do photographs or other measured data.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The escape times, which are converted to colours at the exact centres of the pixels, go to infinity at the border of the set, so colours from centres near borders are unpredictable, due to aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This example has edges in about half of its pixels, so it shows much aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The first image is uploaded at its original sampling rate.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] (Since most modern software anti-aliases, one may have to download the full-size version to see all of the aliasing.) The second image is calculated at five times the sampling rate and down-sampled with anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Assuming that one would really like something like the average colour over each pixel, this one is getting closer.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is clearly more orderly than the first.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In order to properly compare these images, viewing them at full-scale is necessary.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It happens that, in this case, there is additional information that can be used.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] By re-calculating with a "distance estimator" algorithm, points were identified that are very close to the edge of the set, so that unusually fine detail is aliased in from the rapidly changing escape times near the edge of the set.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The colours derived from these calculated points have been identified as unusually unrepresentative of their pixels.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The set changes more rapidly there, so a single point sample is less representative of the whole pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Those points were replaced, in the third image, by interpolating the points around them.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This reduces the noisiness of the image but has the side effect of brightening the colours.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] So this image is not exactly the same that would be obtained with an even larger set of calculated points.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] To show what was discarded, the rejected points, blended into a grey background, are shown in the fourth image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Finally, "Budding Turbines" is so regular that systematic (Moiré) aliasing can clearly be seen near the main "turbine axis" when it is downsized by taking the nearest pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The aliasing in the first image appears random because it comes from all levels of detail, below the pixel size.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When the lower level aliasing is suppressed, to make the third image and then that is down-sampled once more, without anti-aliasing, to make the fifth image, the order on the scale of the third image appears as systematic aliasing in the fifth image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Super sampling anti-aliasing (SSAA), also called full-scene anti-aliasing (FSAA), is used to avoid aliasing (or "jaggies") on full-screen images.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] SSAA was the first type of anti-aliasing available with early video cards.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] But due to its tremendous computational cost and the advent of multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA) support on GPUs, it is no longer widely used in real time applications.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] MSAA provides somewhat lower graphic quality, but also tremendous savings in computational power.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The resulting image of SSAA may seem softer, and should also appear more realistic.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, while useful for photo-like images, a simple anti-aliasing approach (such as super-sampling and then averaging) may actually worsen the appearance of some types of line art or diagrams (making the image appear fuzzy), especially where most lines are horizontal or vertical.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In these cases, a prior grid-fitting step may be useful (see hinting).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In general, super-sampling is a technique of collecting data points at a greater resolution (usually by a power of two) than the final data resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These data points are then combined (down-sampled) to the desired resolution, often just by a simple average.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The combined data points have less visible aliasing artifacts (or moiré patterns).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Full-scene anti-aliasing by super-sampling usually means that each full frame is rendered at double (2x) or quadruple (4x) the display resolution, and then down-sampled to match the display resolution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Thus, a 2x FSAA would render 4 super-sampled pixels for each single pixel of each frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Rendering at larger resolutions will produce better results; however, more processor power is needed, which can degrade performance and frame rate.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sometimes FSAA is implemented in hardware in such a way that a graphical application is unaware the images are being super-sampled and then down-sampled before being displayed.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] A graphics rendering system creates an image based on objects constructed of polygonal primitives; the aliasing effects in the image can be reduced by applying an anti-aliasing scheme only to the areas of the image representing silhouette edges of the objects.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The silhouette edges are anti-aliased by creating anti-aliasing primitives which vary in opacity.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These anti-aliasing primitives are joined to the silhouetted edges, and create a region in the image where the objects appear to blend into the background.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The method has some important advantages over classical methods based on the accumulation buffer since it generates full-scene anti-aliasing in only two passes and does not require the use of additional memory required by the accumulation buffer.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Object-based anti-aliasing was first developed at Silicon Graphics for their Indy workstation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Digital images are usually stored in a gamma-compressed format, but most optical anti-aliasing filters are linear.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] So to down-sample an image in a way that would match optical blurring, one should first convert it to a linear format, then apply the anti-aliasing filter, and finally convert it back to a gamma compressed format.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Using linear arithmetic on a gamma-compressed image results in values which are slightly different from the ideal filter.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This error is larger when dealing with high contrast areas, causing high contrast areas to become dimmer: bright details (such as a cat's whiskers) become visually thinner, and dark details (such as tree branches) become thicker, relative to the optically anti-aliased image.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is individually distorted, meaning outlines become unsmooth after anti-aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because the conversion to and from a linear format greatly slows down the process, and because the differences are usually subtle, most image editing software, including Final Cut Pro and Adobe Photoshop, process images in the gamma-compressed domain.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Most modern GPUs support storing textures in memory in sRGB format, and can perform transformation to linear space and back transparently, with essentially no loss in performance.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Aliasing is manifested in the case of 2D images as moiré pattern and pixelated edges, colloquially known as "jaggies".
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Common signal processing and image processing knowledge suggests that to achieve perfect elimination of aliasing, proper spatial sampling at the Nyquist rate (or higher) after applying a 2D Anti-aliasing filter is required.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] As this approach would require a forward and inverse fourier transformation, computationally less demanding approximations like supersampling were developed to avoid domain switches by staying in the spatial domain ("image domain").
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Supersampling is computationally expensive because it requires much greater video card memory and memory bandwidth, since the amount of buffer used is several times larger.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] A way around this problem is to use a technique known as **adaptive supersampling**, where only pixels at the edges of objects are supersampled.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Initially only a few samples are taken within each pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] If these values are very similar, only these samples are used to determine the color.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The result of this method is that a higher number of samples are calculated only where necessary, thus improving performance.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] When taking samples within a pixel, the sample positions have to be determined in some way.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Although the number of ways in which this can be done is infinite, there are a few ways which are commonly used.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The pixel is split into several sub-pixels, and a sample is taken from the center of each.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Although, due to the regular nature of sampling, aliasing can still occur if a low number of sub-pixels is used.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Also known as stochastic sampling, it avoids the regularity of grid supersampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] However, due to the irregularity of the pattern, samples end up being unnecessary in some areas of the pixel and lacking in others.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The Poisson disk sampling algorithm places the samples randomly, but then checks that any two are not too close.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The end result is an even but random distribution of samples.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The naive "dart throwing" algorithm is extremely slow for large data sets, which once limited its applications for real-time rendering.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] However, many fast algorithms now exist to generate Poisson disk noise, even those with variable density.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] The Delone set provides a mathematical description of such sampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] A modification of the grid algorithm to approximate the Poisson disk.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] A pixel is split into several sub-pixels, but a sample is not taken from the center of each, but from a random point within the sub-pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] Congregation can still occur, but to a lesser degree.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] A 2×2 grid layout is used but the sample pattern is rotated to avoid samples aligning on the horizontal or vertical axis, greatly improving antialiasing quality for the most commonly encountered cases.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/supersampling] For an optimal pattern, the rotation angle is arctan (⁠1/2⁠) (about 26.6°) and the square is stretched by a factor of ⁠√5/2⁠, making it also a 4-queens solution.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The modern definition of TAA is a spatial anti-aliasing technique for real-time computer graphics that reuses information from previously rendered frames to remove aliasing, such as jaggies, from the current frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The term *temporal anti-aliasing* is somewhat of a misnomer, and this technique is formally referred to as *temporally-amortized supersampling.* It is also known as TXAA (an implementation by Nvidia) or *Temporal Super-Sampling Anti-Aliasing* (TSSAA).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] This method can achieve results comparable to supersampling, at a small fraction of the computational cost, but produces soft images and can cause ghosting.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA popularized in video games in the 2010s, with two early examples being Halo: Reach and Crysis 2, and is now the most common form of spatial anti-aliasing in real-time rendering and game engines.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is sampled at a slightly different position each frame, which is achieved by adding a 2D offset to each frame, a "jitter" that shifts the image by a fraction of the size of a pixel, horizontally and vertically.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The jitter changes each frame, following a pattern (such as a Halton sequence) so that every point in the image is sampled evenly over time.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Old frames are blended into the current frame, accumulating historical rendering data, approaching the result of supersampling over time.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Changes to the scene—such as moving objects, camera motion, or changes in lighting—often mean that the history for any given pixel may be somewhere else on screen, be invalid, or may not exist at all.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Failure to account for these changes results in ghosting.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] To account for movement, velocity vectors are maintained in the G-buffer, allowing the location of each pixel in the previous frame to be calculated.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The pixel at that location in the previous frame is accumulated into a history buffer, at its new location.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Accurate velocities are required to prevent smearing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Often, the historical data for a pixel will become invalid due to changes in occlusion, such as the pixel having recently become visible after being blocked by an object last frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] This causes ghosting unless it is detected: One method is to compare the depth of the historical position to the depth values in the current pixel's neighborhood.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Color can also be useful for validating the history of a pixel, since a sudden change in color can indicate new lighting conditions or an incorrect pixel velocity.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] A drawback of TAA is that it does not work well with transparent objects, particles, or reflections, because they can produce incorrect velocity vectors.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] In the case of transparency, this is because only one velocity vector can typically be stored per pixel.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Dithering can be used to simulate opacity, a technique known as *screen-door transparency*, which works with TAA and is smoothed out over time by it.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Ghosting and blurriness are two disadvantages specific to TAA, though both can be significantly reduced with proper implementation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA requires more engine- and game-specific tuning than other anti-aliasing methods to achieve acceptable results; poorly-tuned implementations can severely exacerbate TAA's issues in some situations.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Brute force supersampling (rendering at a higher resolution and downsampling), which is considered a gold standard for spatial anti-aliasing, is very costly compared to TAA, which can produce comparable results in many situations.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA), which was previously the most common real-time spatial anti-aliasing method, does not work well with deferred shading, which is needed for a number of common rendering techniques.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Several post-processing anti-aliasing methods were developed to overcome this limitation, such as fast approximate anti-aliasing (FXAA), and morphological anti-aliasing (MLAA).
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] These methods can have poor temporal stability, such as causing flickering artifacts.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA generally reduces aliasing better than these methods, is more temporally stable, and still works with deferred shading.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Deep learning super sampling (DLSS), developed by Nvidia, operates on similar principles to TAA.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] DLSS uses machine learning to combine samples in the current frame and past frames, and it can be thought of as an advanced TAA implementation.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The traditional definition of TAA is the removal of temporal aliasing.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] A photograph collects light over a period of time, called an exposure.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] This can result in moving objects exhibiting motion blur, which is sometimes a desirable effect.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, images are often rendered at a single instant in time, ignoring the effects of motion, for convenience.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] This results in temporal aliasing: moving objects can appear to jump or flash between frames as their position changes.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] This effect can be mitigated, but not eliminated, by using a higher refresh rate display, and increasing the frame rate to match the refresh rate.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Another approach, analogous to spatial supersampling, is to simulate motion blur by rendering many instants in time, integrating them into each frame.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Aliasing is a result of the sampling theorem of signal processing: To avoid it, a signal must be sampled at a rate at least twice the highest frequency present in the signal.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] An example of temporal aliasing is the wagon-wheel effect, where spinning objects can appear to move slowly, stop, or reverse.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Temporal aliasing can also affect film and video.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] The shutter behavior of the sampling system (the camera) strongly influences aliasing, because the window function of the exposure (its shape over time) determines how well bandlimited the image signal is before sampling.
[src:anti-aliasing-graphics/temporal-anti-aliasing] Different window functions can be chosen to reduce temporal aliasing.
